******
[2]
Date: Fri 3 Jun 2011
Source: JoongAng Daily [edited]
http://joongangdaily.joins.com/article/view.asp?aid=2937090


After a month of epidemiological investigation on the mystery lung
malady that has stricken pregnant women and killed 3, the Korea
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said yesterday [2 Jun 2011]
they concluded it wasn't a virus, wasn't contagious and wasn't a new
phenomenon either. But they don't know what caused it and are baffled
as to why it's showing up in pregnant women.

"For the past month, we have studied lung disease patients in
intensive care units of 44 hospitals throughout the country and
concluded that there haven't been additional occurrences of this
disease," said an official from the KCDC. "This disease should no
longer be called a virus but an unidentified severe lung disease."

Since May [2011], 8 patients have been confirmed stricken with the
disease, which leads to pulmonary fibrosis, or scarring of the lungs,
7 of them pregnant women and one a man in his 40s. One of the women
died 10 May and the 2nd on 26 May [2011].

During the month-long investigation, 3 pregnant women visited
hospitals complaining of difficulty breathing. After conducting
biopsies, 2 were cleared of having the disease, and the 3d was
hospitalized 30 May [2011] for more tests, according to the KCDC.

The KCDC held an advisory meeting on Wednesday [1 Jun 2011] and came
to a conclusion that this "unidentified lung disease is not new." It
said that there have been "reports of patients, including both
children and adults, suffering from the same disease since 2005" and
that "only the exact cause of the disease is not specified yet."

The KCDC said it had no medical grounds for stating that pregnant
women are more vulnerable to the disease.

Health authorities said that the rash of cases should be described as
"an increase of pregnant women suffering from the lung disease rather
than a collective occurrence, as there are no statistical data to back
up such a statement."

Said Oh Myoung-don, a professor of internal medicine at Seoul
National University College of Medicine: "The old and the infirm and
chronic invalids with reduced immunity are more vulnerable to
infectious respiratory diseases, but this unknown lung disease wasn't
found in those patients. Therefore, the possibility of this disease
being infectious is extremely low."

[Byline: Yim Seung-hye, Park Yu-mi]

