******
[5]
Date: Mon 13 Jun 2011
Source: KBS News [in Korean, machine trans. edited]
http://news.kbs.co.kr/science/2011/06/13/2306924.html


Suddenly, the lungs become hard in this lung disease of unknown
cause. As of yesterday [12 Jun 2011], there were confirmed cases of
interfamily occurrence. Hospitalized for breathing difficulties late
last month [May 2011] in Seoul followed by surgery for lung
transplantation at a university hospital, a 26-year-old pregnant woman
and her 23-month-old son were found to be suffering from the pulmonary
fibrosis phenomenon.

Families [of patients] will be checked again in the additional cases.
Earlier yesterday [12 Jun 2011], a mother and 2 daughters in a family
with severe acute lung disease were also reported as cases.

What they have in common is rapid, labored hard breathing as
interstitial pneumonitis; the lungs become hard.

[Korean] Centers for Disease Control Infectious Disease Management
Center staff said in an interview that, "according to our
investigation, there may be spread among family members infected with
pathogens that cause [the disease], but that has not been
determined."

Until now, the lung disease occurred in 3 pregnant women who died.
However, it is salient that disease has been seen in familial cases of
non-pregnant adults and children. In fact, for the past 5 years,
excluding pregnant adults or children with this disease, it has killed
472 people.

