[6]
Date: Sun 12 Jun 2011
Source: YTN [in Korean, machine trans. edited]
http://www.ytn.co.kr/_ln/0105_201106121741203449


A 32-year-old living in Seoul and his 6-year-old daughter had
shortness of breath; their symptoms deteriorated in the hospital in
Seoul, says the university. Also, the patient's one-year-old daughter,
because she had the same symptoms, was in the hospital in Busan.

The Centers for Disease Control, however, indicated recently that the
lung disease killed an unknown number of women who had different
symptoms, [those of] pneumonia. It stated that they likely
deteriorated.

The daughter currently is [breathing] without relying on a respirator
and artificial lungs and is waiting for a lung transplant.

--
Communicated by:
Ronan Kelly
<ronankelly@comcast.net>

[Many reports on this undiagnosed lung disease have been appearing in
the popular Korean press. It has been difficult to determine the exact
number of pulmonary fibrosis cases, specific deaths due to it, and the
dates and places of occurrence of these cases. Some reports refer to a
virus, yet virus etiology has been discarded by the Korean CDC.

As Mod.CP indicated in the ProMED-mail post of 26 May 2011
(ProMED-mail archive no. 20110526.1614): "Pulmonary fibrosis can be
caused by many conditions, including chronic inflammatory processes
(sarcoidosis, Wegener's granulomatosis), infections, environmental
agents (asbestos, silica, exposure to certain gases), exposure to
ionizing radiation (such as radiation therapy to treat tumors of the
chest), chronic conditions (lupus, rheumatoid arthritis), and certain
medications." For further information, see the previous ProMED-mail
post (referenced below) and MedicineNet.com at
http://www.medicinenet.com/pulmonary_fibrosis/article.htm#tocb).

ProMED will appreciate receiving additional information about the
number of cases and their etiology as it becomes available. - Mod.TY]

[For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea, see
http://healthmap.org/r/00bh. - Mod.MPP]]
